Name: Bab_al-Nasr_(Cairo)
Description: Bab al-Nasr - 11th-century Fatimid gate with twin towers, Arabic calligraphy, and original iron-reinforced doors protecting Islamic Cairo

Name: Mortuary_Temple_of_Seti_I_in_Qurna
Description: Built by Pharaoh Seti I (1290-1279 BCE). Features well-preserved reliefs, hypostyle halls, and connections to his royal tomb in Valley of the Kings. Located near Deir el-Bahari.

Name: Great_Pyramid_of_Giza
Description: Oldest of the Seven Wonders (c. 2560 BCE). Built for Pharaoh Khufu. Original height: 146.6m (now 138.5m). Interior access to Grand Gallery & King's Chamber. Part of Giza Necropolis with Sphinx.

Name: Umm_Kulthum_Museum
Description: Dedicated to "The Voice of Egypt" (1898-1975). Displays personal items, recordings, and multimedia exhibits about her legendary music career in Cairo's Manasterly Palace.

Name: Wadi_el-Raiyan
Description: Protected desert valley with waterfalls, lakes, and fossil dunes. Famous for its two connected lakes formed by agricultural runoff and unique desert wildlife.

Name: Al-Shate'e_Mosque
Description: Modern mosque in 6th of October City with distinctive circular design and twin minarets. Known for its spacious prayer hall and Islamic calligraphy.

Name: Wadi_el_Gemal_National_Park
Description: Coastal desert park with mountains, coral reefs, and archaeological sites. Home to endangered species like dugongs and gazelles. Popular for diving and hiking.

Name: Bayt_Al-Suhaymi
Description: 17th-century Ottoman-era house in Islamic Cairo, featuring mashrabiya screens, courtyards, and traditional residential architecture.

Name: Na'ama_Bay
Description: Sharm El Sheikh's most famous bay with coral reefs, luxury resorts, beach clubs, and vibrant nightlife. Hub for diving and water sports.

Name: Elephantine
Description: Ancient Nile island with Khnum Temple ruins, Nilometer, and Aswan Museum. Key Pharaonic trading post near Aswan's First Cataract.

Name: Siwa
Description: Isolated Saharan oasis with Oracle Temple ruins, mud-brick Shali fortress, and natural salt lakes. Center of unique Berber culture.

Name: Colossi_of_Memnon
Description: Two massive 18th-dynasty statues (14m tall) of Amenhotep III. Originally guarded his mortuary temple (now destroyed). Famous for ancient "singing" phenomenon.

Name: Pyramid_of_Unas
Description: Oldest known pyramid with Pyramid Texts (c. 2340 BCE). Built for Pharaoh Unas, featuring inscribed burial chamber and causeway ruins near Step Pyramid.

Name: Cairo_Citadel
Description: 12th-century Islamic fortress with Muhammad Ali Mosque, museums, and panoramic Cairo views. Built by Salah ad-Din (Saladin).

Name: Mastabat_al-Fir'aun
Description: 4th-dynasty rectangular tomb (c. 2500 BCE) for Pharaoh Shepseskaf. Unique flat-topped design, built in red sandstone. Located south of Saqqara's main pyramid field.

Name: Great_Hypostyle_Hall_of_Karnak
Description: New Kingdom hall (c. 1290-1224 BCE) with 134 massive columns. Built by Seti I & Ramses II. Largest religious columned hall in the world.

Name: Wadi_Degla
Description: Protected desert valley near Cairo with fossil beds, limestone cliffs, and hiking trails. Important paleontological site showing ancient marine fossils.

Name: Abu_Haggag_Mosque
Description: 13th-century mosque built into Luxor Temple's courtyard. Unique coexistence of Pharaonic and Islamic architecture. Hosts annual Sufi festival.

Name: Gayer-Anderson_Museum
Description: 17th-century Ottoman house in Cairo with antique collections. Named after British officer who restored it. Features mashrabiya screens and period furnishings.

Name: Bab_Zuwayla
Description: 11th-century Fatimid gate with twin minarets. Last remaining southern entrance to medieval Cairo. Execution site of Sultan Tumanbay.

Name: Bagawat
Description: 4th-century Christian necropolis in Kharga Oasis. Features 263 mudbrick tombs with Coptic frescoes. One of oldest preserved Christian cemeteries.

Name: Temple_of_Seti_I_in_Abydos
Description: 13th-century BCE temple with exquisite reliefs. Features the Abydos King List and seven sanctuaries dedicated to different gods. Built by Seti I, completed by Ramses II.

Name: Sehel_Island
Description: Granite island near Aswan with 250+ ancient inscriptions. Famous for the Famine Stela (Ptolemaic copy of Old Kingdom text). Local Nubian village on site.

Name: Karnak_precinct_of_Amun-Ra
Description: Vast temple complex in Thebes covering 2.4km². Center of Amun worship for 2000 years, featuring the Great Hypostyle Hall and Hatshepsut's obelisks.

Name: Pyramid_of_Djoser
Description: World's oldest stone pyramid (c. 2650 BCE). Step design by Imhotep for Pharaoh Djoser. First large-scale cut stone construction.

Name: Pyramid_of_Djedefra
Description: 4th-dynasty pyramid (2580-2570 BCE) with unique red granite casing. Built by Khufu's successor Djedefre at Egypt's highest elevation site.

Name: KV17
Description: Longest (& most decorated) tomb in Valley of Kings (137m). 19th-dynasty pharaoh's burial with complete astronomical ceiling and vibrant reliefs.

Name: Al-Ashraf_Mosque
Description: Mamluk-era mosque (1425 CE) near Cairo Citadel. Features twin minarets and intricate stonework. Built by Sultan Al-Ashraf Barsbay.

Name: Temple_of_Kom_Ombo
Description: Unique double temple (2nd century BCE) dedicated to Sobek (crocodile god) and Horus. Features surgical tools relief and crocodile mummy museum.

Name: City_of_the_dead_(Cairo)
Description: Vast Islamic-era necropolis with Mamluk tombs and modern residential areas. Features Sultan Qaitbey's complex and living communities among mausoleums.

Name: Egyptian_Museum_(Cairo)
Description: World's largest collection of Pharaonic antiquities (120,000+ items). Houses Tutankhamun's treasures and Old Kingdom artifacts in iconic pink building.

Name: Saint_George_Church_in_Coptic_Cairo
Description: Only circular church in Coptic Cairo, built atop Roman fortress ruins. Features suspended icon of St. George and ancient crypts.

Name: Red_Pyramid
Description: First successful true pyramid (c. 2590 BCE). Built by Sneferu with red limestone. 104m tall with accessible burial chambers.

Name: El_Ferdan_Railway_Bridge
Description: World's longest swing bridge (340m). Crosses Suez Canal near Ismailia. Original 1918 structure rebuilt twice after wars.

Name: Qasr_Qarun
Description: Ptolemaic-era temple (3rd century BCE) in Fayoum oasis. Dedicated to Sobek and Dionysus, with intact roof and mysterious locked chambers.

Name: Kitchener's_Island
Description: Botanical garden island in Aswan. Gifted to Lord Kitchener (1899), featuring 400+ exotic plants and royal palm avenues.

Name: Children's_Civilisation_and_Creativity_Centre
Description: Interactive museum in Heliopolis teaching Egyptian history through hands-on exhibits. Features replica tombs and STEM workshops.

Name: Sulayman_Agha_al-Silahdar_Mosque
Description: Ottoman-era mosque (1839) on Muizz Street. Notable for its pink-and-green striped stone facade and double minarets. Built by Muhammad Ali's arms-bearer.

Name: Temple_of_Hibis
Description: Persian-era temple (6th century BCE) in Kharga Oasis. Best-preserved Late Period structure with Amun worship reliefs and Persian kings' cartouches.

Name: Valley_of_the_Golden_Mummies
Description: Roman-era necropolis (1st-2nd century CE) in Bahariya Oasis. Contains 100+ gilded mummies with Greco-Roman death masks in underground galleries.

Name: Giza_Zoo
Description: Historic 1891 zoological garden with 1,200+ animals. Features rare species exhibits and 19th-century iron-and-glass pavilions.

Name: Bibliotheca_Alexandrina
Description: Modern revival of ancient library (2002). Houses 8 million books, planetarium, and manuscript museum on Mediterranean coast.

Name: Unfinished_obelisk_in_Aswan
Description: Abandoned 42m obelisk (New Kingdom era) still attached to bedrock. Showcases ancient stone-working techniques in Aswan's granite quarries.

Name: Sabil_of_Abd_al-Rahman_Katkhuda
Description: 18th-century Ottoman public water fountain (1744) with ornate tilework. Architectural centerpiece of historic Cairo's streetscape.

Name: Agiba_beach
Description: Secluded Mediterranean cove near Marsa Matrouh. Famous for turquoise waters, golden cliffs, and natural rock arch. Accessible via steep staircase.

Name: Gebel_el-Silsila
Description: Ancient sandstone quarry site with New Kingdom shrines. Source of temple blocks for Karnak and Luxor. Features rock-cut stelae and Nile-side cenotaphs.

Name: Muizz_Street
Description: Medieval thoroughfare in Islamic Cairo with 30+ monuments. Showcases 1,000 years of architecture from Fatimid to Ottoman eras.

Name: Monastery_of_Saint_Bishoy
Description: 4th-century Coptic monastery in Wadi El Natrun. Houses Saint Bishoy's relics and Pope Shenouda III's tomb. Fortified walls and ancient manuscripts.

Name: Osireion
Description: Mysterious underground structure (possibly New Kingdom) at Abydos. Granite megalithic architecture linked to Osiris worship. Flooded central hall with symbolic imagery.

Name: Pyramid_of_Khafra
Description: Second-tallest Giza pyramid (136m). Built by Khafre (c. 2570 BCE) with intact limestone casing at apex. Includes valley temple and Sphinx connection.

Name: Soma_Bay
Description: Exclusive Red Sea peninsula with 5-star resorts. Features private beaches, kitesurfing hotspots, and coral reefs. Near Hurghada (30km south).

Name: Madrasah_of_Sarghatmish
Description: 14th-century Mamluk madrasa (1356 CE) near Cairo Citadel. Unique cruciform layout with four iwans. Active Sufi prayer space.

Name: Corniche_(Alexandria)
Description: 15km Mediterranean waterfront promenade. Historic harbor views with seafood restaurants, 19th-century buildings, and access to beaches. Best at sunset.

Name: St._Catherine's_Cathedral,_Alexandria
Description: Neo-Byzantine Catholic cathedral (1856). Features Italian marble altar, stained glass, and Mediterranean-facing facade. Seat of Alexandria's Latin Patriarch.

Name: Giza_pyramid_complex
Description: Ancient 4th-dynasty necropolis featuring Khufu's Great Pyramid, Khafre's complex with Sphinx, and Menkaure's pyramid. UNESCO World Heritage Site.

Name: Monastery_of_Saint_Anthony
Description: Oldest active Christian monastery (356 CE) near Red Sea mountains. Contains original 4th-century cave church and medieval frescoes.

Name: Alexandria_Opera_House
Description: Restored 1929 Italian-style theater. Hosts classical concerts, ballet, and Arabic opera in historic downtown.

Name: Sphinx_of_Memphis
Description: 4m-long alabaster sphinx (New Kingdom era). Guarded Memphis' Temple of Ptah. Now displayed outdoors at Mit Rahina Museum.

Name: Grand_Egyptian_Museum
Description: World's largest archaeology museum near Giza Pyramids. Houses 50,000+ artifacts including full Tutankhamun collection and Khufu solar boat.

Name: Kom_el-Shoqafa
Description: Roman-era catacombs (2nd century CE) blending Egyptian/Greek art. Three-tiered underground necropolis with unique hybrid sarcophagi and reliefs.

Name: Qaed_Ibrahim_Mosque
Description: 19th-century Alexandrian mosque (1848) with Ottoman-style twin minarets. Built by Muhammad Ali's governor over ancient theater ruins.

Name: Khayrbak_Mosque
Description: 16th-century Mamluk-Ottoman hybrid mosque (1520 CE). Features defensive tower and intricate stalactite portal. Built by last Mamluk sultan's deputy.

Name: Ramesseum
Description: Ramses II's memorial temple (13th century BCE). Features fallen colossus (original weight: 1,000 tons) and well-preserved battle reliefs.

Name: Al-Qurn
Description: Pyramid-shaped peak (457m) overlooking Valley of the Kings. Believed sacred to Hathor and Meretseger in ancient times. Hiking routes available.

Name: Garden_City,_Cairo
Description: Early 20th-century planned district with Belle Époque villas and circular streets. Designed as European-style garden suburb along the Nile.

Name: Tomb_of_Nefertari
Description: QV66 - Most ornate tomb in Valley of the Queens (1290-1255 BCE). Stunning polychrome reliefs of Ramses II's favorite wife. Strict visitor limits.

Name: Monastery_of_Saint_Simeon_in_Aswan
Description: 7th-century fortress monastery abandoned after 1173 CE. Features Nubian-style domed church, monk cells, and desert-facing defensive walls. Reachable by camel or 4x4.

Name: Temple_of_Isis_in_Philae
Description: Ptolemaic-Roman temple (380 BCE-300 CE) relocated to Agilkia Island. Last active pagan temple in Mediterranean world (closed 550 CE).

Name: Blue_Hole_(Red_Sea)
Description: Underwater sinkhole near Dahab. 130m deep with coral walls and arch at 56m. Famous among technical divers (requires certification).

Name: Baron_Empain_Palace
Description: 1907 Hindu-inspired palace in Heliopolis. Built by Belgian industrialist with rotating dome and underground tunnels. Recently restored.

Name: Saint_Catherine's_Monastery,_Mount_Sinai
Description: 6th-century Byzantine monastery at Moses' biblical site. Houses world's oldest continuously operating library (3,500+ manuscripts). UNESCO site.

Name: Faiyum_Zoo
Description: 1930s landscaped zoo with lake views. Features rare Faiyum fauna and historic botanical gardens. Renovated in 2021.

Name: Aguilkia_Island
Description: Artificial island created to house relocated Philae Temple complex. Designed to mimic original temple orientation.

Name: Hanging_Church_(Cairo)
Description: 7th-century Coptic church built atop Roman fortress gates. Famous for its suspended nave and 110+ icons (oldest from 8th century).

Name: Qubbet_el-Hawa
Description: Noblemen's tombs (6th-12th dynasties) near Aswan. Features panoramic Nile views and inscriptions documenting Nubian trade expeditions.

Name: Ptolemaic_Temple_of_Hathor_in_Deir_el-Medina
Description: Greco-Roman era temple (3rd century BCE) honoring Hathor. Built by Ptolemy IV atop earlier shrines. Features vivid astronomical ceiling.

Name: Tomb_of_Nakht_TT52
Description: 18th-dynasty scribe's tomb (c. 1400 BCE) with famous banquet scenes. Best-preserved daily life frescoes in Thebes.

Name: Abdeen_Palace
Description: 19th-century royal palace (1874) blending Ottoman and European styles. Now houses military and presidential gifts museums. Central Cairo landmark

Name: Deir_el-Medina
Description: Ancient workers' village (1550-1070 BCE) for Valley of the Kings artisans. Preserved houses, tombs (TT1-TT9), and ostraca records of daily life.

Name: Egyptian_National_Military_Museum
Description: Citadel-based museum showcasing 7,000+ years of warfare. Features Pharaonic weapons, Napoleon's cannon, and modern army displays.

Name: Madrasah_of_Al-Nasir_Muhammad
Description: 14th-century Mamluk school (1295-1303) in Cairo Citadel. Features Quranic calligraphy and innovative dome acoustics. Built by Sultan Al-Nasir.

Name: Al-Manyal_Palace_Museum
Description: Early 20th-century royal retreat (1903) with Islamic gardens. Showcases Prince Mohammed Ali's collections of art, manuscripts, and exotic taxidermy.

Name: Monastery_of_Saint_Samuel_the_Confessor
Description: 5th-century Coptic monastery near Maghagha. Contains cave cells of St. Samuel and 12th-century frescoes. Pilgrimage site for infertile women.

Name: Meidum
Description: 3rd-dynasty step pyramid (c. 2600 BCE) collapsed into tower-like form. Possibly Sneferu's first pyramid attempt with intact mortuary temple.

Name: Abu_el-Abbas_el-Mursi_Mosque
Description: 13th-century Andalusian-style mosque (1307) in Alexandria. Tomb of Sufi saint Abu Abbas al-Mursi. Features 4 domes

Name: Theban_Necropolis
Description: Vast West Bank burial complex (1500-1000 BCE) containing Valley of the Kings, Queens, and over 1,000 noble tombs. UNESCO World Heritage Site.

Name: Citadel_of_Qaitbay
Description: 15th-century fortress (1477 CE) on Alexandria's Mediterranean coast. Built by Sultan Qaitbay using Pharos Lighthouse ruins. Features naval museum and harbor views.

Name: Nabq_Protected_Area
Description: 600km² Red Sea coastal reserve near Sharm El Sheikh. Features mangrove forests, coral reefs, and rare wildlife like Nubian ibex.

Name: Mosque_of_al-Mahmudiya
Description: Ottoman-era mosque (1567) in Alexandria with unique double prayer niche. Built over ancient Temple of Isis using Roman columns.

Name: Bibliotheca_Alexandrina_planetarium
Description: Modern 120-seat dome theater (2002) with advanced Digistar projection. Features astronomy exhibits and NASA collaborations.

Name: Al-Jawhara_Palace_museum
Description: 19th-century royal palace (1814) in Cairo Citadel. Built by Muhammad Ali with Ottoman-Egyptian decor. Houses royal artifacts and historic throne room.

Name: Aswan_High_Dam
Description: 1960s mega-dam (3,830m long) creating Lake Nasser. Soviet-Egyptian project that controls Nile floods and provides hydroelectric power.

Name: Mortuary_Temple_of_Hatshepsut
Description: 15th-century BCE terraced temple at Deir el-Bahari. Dedicated to female pharaoh Hatshepsut, with colonnaded shrines to Hathor and Anubis.

Name: Deir_el-Bahari
Description: Cliffside temple complex featuring Hatshepsut's terraced sanctuary, Mentuhotep II's tomb-temple, and Thutmose III's shrines. UNESCO World Heritage Site.

Name: El_Alamein_Military_Museum
Description: WWII museum (1956) documenting North Africa campaigns. Features Allied/Axis weaponry, dioramas, and the El Alamein Commonwealth Cemetery.

Name: Pompey's_Pillar,_Alexandria
Description: 27m red granite column (297 CE) honoring Diocletian. Last remaining structure from Alexandria's Serapeum temple complex. Surrounded by sphinxes and underground galleries.

Name: Esna_Temple
Description: Ptolemaic-Roman temple (186-250 CE) dedicated to Khnum. Famous for intact hypostyle hall with 24 columns and zodiac ceiling carvings.

Name: Pyramid_of_Amenemhat_III_in_Hawara
Description: 12th-dynasty mudbrick pyramid (c. 1850 BCE) with labyrinthine interior. Originally cased in white limestone, now eroded to core structure.

Name: Great_Sphinx_of_Giza
Description: 4th-dynasty limestone statue (c. 2500 BCE) with lion's body and human head. Measures 73m long × 20m tall. Linked to Khafre's pyramid complex.

Name: Rahmanyia_island
Description: Nile island near Beni Suef with palm groves and birdwatching spots. Popular for picnics and traditional fishing boats (feluccas).

Name: Al-Azhar_Park_(Cairo)
Description: 30-hectare green space (2005) built atop historic Cairo landfill. Features Fatimid-era walls, fountains, and panoramic city views.

Name: Deir_el-Muharraq
Description: 6th-century Coptic monastery in Qusia. Believed to host the Holy Family's cave for 6 months. Features ancient icons and annual August pilgrimage.

Name: Shalalat_Garden,_Alexandria
Description: Coastal park (1942) with waterfall features and Mediterranean views. Known for its illuminated evening fountain shows.

Name: Eliyahu_Hanavi_Synagogue_(Alexandria)
Description: 14th-century Jewish temple rebuilt 1850. Features neo-Gothic arches, Italian marble, and one of Egypt's last active Jewish communities.

Name: Orman_Garden
Description: 1875 botanical garden in Giza with 7,000+ plant species. Features royal-era greenhouses and annual spring flower festival.

Name: Fatimid_Cemetery_in_Aswan
Description: 11th-century Islamic necropolis with distinctive domed mausoleums. Features Kubbat al-Hawa windcatcher tombs and Nubian-influenced brickwork.

Name: Famine_stele
Description: 11th-century Islamic necropolis with domed mausoleums. Features Nubian-influenced brickwork and Kubbat al-Hawa windcatcher tombs.

Name: Mokattam
Description: Ptolemaic-era granite inscription (200 BCE) recounting a 3rd-dynasty famine. Located on Sehel Island near Aswan.

Name: Aquarium_Grotto_Garden
Description: Limestone plateau overlooking Cairo. Famous for Cave Church and Zabaleen recycling community. Panoramic city views.

Name: Gezira
Description: 1902 Art Nouveau aquarium with grotto-style tanks. Houses Nile and Red Sea species in Alexandria's Antoniades Gardens.

Name: Mausoleum_of_Aga_Khan
Description: Nile island hosting Cairo Tower and Opera House. Green space in central Cairo with luxury hotels.

Name: Great_Temple_of_the_Aten
Description: 1959 white marble mausoleum for Aga Khan III. Offers panoramic views of Aswan and the Nile.

Name: Qasr_al-Nil_Bridge
Description: New Kingdom temple (1350 BCE) at Amarna. Built by Akhenaten with open-air design for sun worship.

Name: Temple_of_Khonsu_in_Karnak
Description: 1931 steel bridge connecting downtown Cairo to Zamalek. Features iconic lion statues.

Name: Beni_Hassan
Description: New Kingdom temple (1198 BCE) dedicated to moon god Khonsu. Features astronomical ceiling.

Name: Kiosk_of_Trajan_in_Philae
Description: Middle Kingdom tombs (2000 BCE) with wrestling and military scenes. 39 rock-cut tombs in Minya governorate.

Name: Khan_el-Khalili
Description: Roman-era kiosk (100 CE) with 14 columns. Served as ceremonial entrance to Philae Temple.

Name: Luxor_Temple
Description: 14th-century bazaar in Islamic Cairo. Gold market, spice stalls, and historic coffeehouses.

Name: Suez_Canal_Bridge
Description: New Kingdom temple (1400 BCE) dedicated to Amun. Connected to Karnak by Avenue of Sphinxes.

Name: Pyramid_of_Senusret_II
Description: 2001 cable-stayed bridge ("Egypt-Japan Friendship Bridge") spanning Suez Canal at El Qantara.

Name: Pyramid_of_Neferirkare
Description: 12th-dynasty pyramid (1887 BCE) at El Lahun. Mudbrick core with complex internal passages.

Name: Pyramid_of_Qakare_Ibi
Description: 5th-dynasty pyramid (2445 BCE) at Abusir. Originally 52m tall, now heavily eroded.

Name: Giza_Plateau
Description: 8th-dynasty pyramid (2160 BCE) at Saqqara. Smallest royal pyramid (21m tall).

Name: Sultan_Qaytbay_Complex
Description: Giza archaeological zone containing Great Pyramid, Sphinx, and worker villages.

Name: Pyramid_of_Menkaure
Description: 15th-century Mamluk complex (1474 CE) with mosque, madrasa, and sabil. Fine carved stonework.

Name: Amr_Ibn_al-Aas_Mosque_(Damietta)
Description: 4th-dynasty pyramid (2510 BCE) standing 65m tall. Valley Temple displays triad statues.

Name: Montaza_Palace
Description: 7th-century mosque (642 CE) in Damietta. Egypt's second-oldest mosque after Amr Ibn al-Aas (Cairo).

Name: 6_October_Bridge
Description: 1932 royal gardens and palace in Alexandria. Turkish-Florentine architecture with private beach.

Name: Ben_Ezra_Synagogue
Description: 1996 cable-stayed bridge (20.5km long). Connects central Cairo to outer districts.

Name: Bent_Pyramid
Description: 9th-century synagogue housing Geniza documents. Legendary site of baby Moses' rescue.

Name: Crystal_Mountain,_White_Desert
Description: 4th-dynasty "bent" pyramid (2600 BCE) showing architectural transition from step to smooth sides.

Name: Pyramid_of_Djedkare_Isesi
Description: Quartz crystal formations in Farafra Depression. Sparkles in sunlight like gemstones.

Name: Alexandria_Zoo
Description: 5th-dynasty pyramid (2410 BCE) at Saqqara. First pyramid with Pyramid Texts inside.

Name: Monastery_of_Saint_Macarius_the_Great
Description: 1903 zoological garden in Alexandria. Features rare species and historic cages.

Name: Pyramid_of_Userkaf
Description: 4th-century Coptic monastery in Wadi Natrun. Houses Pope Shenouda III's tomb and ancient manuscripts.

Name: Valley_of_the_Queens
Description: New Kingdom necropolis for royal wives/princes. Contains 80+ tombs including Nefertari's (QV66) with vibrant murals.

Name: Cairo_International_Stadium
Description: Africa's largest stadium (1960). Hosts football matches and concerts. Capacity: 75,000.

Name: Sakakini_Palace
Description: 1897 Italianate palace in Cairo. Mix of Rococo and Islamic styles with ornate interiors.

Name: Dendera_Temple_complex
Description: Ptolemaic-Roman temple (1st century BCE). Famous for Hathor columns and zodiac ceiling.

Name: Islamic_Cairo
Description: Medieval district with 500+ monuments. Includes Al-Muizz Street and Khan el-Khalili.

Name: Ras_Muhammad
Description: Red Sea national park with coral reefs and shark observatory. Prime diving spot.

Name: Mosque_of_al-Maridani
Description: 14th-century Mamluk mosque (1339). Notable for stained glass and marble minbar.

Name: Greco-Roman_Museum,_Alexandria
Description: 1895 museum with 40,000+ Greco-Roman artifacts. Statues of Serapis and Alexander.

Name: Synagogue_of_Moses_Maimonides
Description: 12th-century synagogue honoring Jewish philosopher. Near Ben Ezra in Cairo.

Name: Mosque_of_Saint_Ibrahim_El-Desouky
Description: 17th-century mosque (1666) in Desouk. Annual moulid attracts thousands.

Name: Al-Sayeda_Nafeesah_Mosque
Description: 9th-century shrine to Prophet's granddaughter. Silver-domed mausoleum.

Name: Saint_Barbara_Church_in_Coptic_Cairo
Description: 5th-century church with Byzantine icons. Dedicated to martyred saint.

Name: Temple_of_Derr
Description: Ramses II rock-cut temple relocated during Aswan Dam construction.

Name: Alexandria_Port
Description: Ancient harbor with modern shipping. Includes Qaitbay Citadel and breakwaters.

Name: Mosque-Madrassa_of_Sultan_Hassan
Description: 14th-century Mamluk complex (1356). Massive 68m minaret and four madrasas.

Name: Bab_al-Futuh
Description: 11th-century Fatimid gate (1087). Part of Cairo's medieval walls with twin towers.

Name: Qalawun_complex
Description: 13th-century hospital-mosque-madrasa (1284). Early Mamluk architecture.

Name: Saint_Mark's_Coptic_Orthodox_Cathedral,_Cairo
Description: 1968 cathedral seating 5,000. Seat of Coptic Orthodox Pope.

Name: Coptic_Museum_in_Cairo
Description: 1910 museum with Coptic art, textiles, and Nag Hammadi manuscripts.

Name: Nilometer_in_Rhoda_Island
Description: 9th-century Nilometer measuring flood levels. Abbasid-era stonework.

Name: San_Stefano_Grand_Plaza
Description: Landmark 2007 Mediterranean-facing mall with luxury brands and marina.

Name: Mohandessin
Description: Affluent Cairo district with art deco buildings and modern cafes.

Name: Speos_Artemidos
Description: 15th-century BCE rock temple of Hatshepsut. Dedicated to Pakhet.

Name: Pyramid_of_Khendjer
Description: 13th-dynasty pyramid (1760 BCE) at Saqqara. Mudbrick with limestone casing.

Name: Al-Salih_Tala'i_Mosque
Description: 10th-century mosque (1160) with unique hanging entrance.

Name: Mallawi_Museum
Description: Small museum with Amarna-era artifacts. Rebuilt after 2013 looting.

Name: Amir_Taz_Palace
Description: 14th-century Mamluk palace (1352). Now hosts cultural events.

Name: Pyramid_of_Sahure
Description: 5th-dynasty pyramid (2480 BCE) at Abusir. First with pyramid texts.

Name: Al-Rifa'i_Mosque
Description: 19th-century mosque (1912) housing royal tombs including King Farouk's.

Name: Mosque_of_Qajmas_al-Ishaqi
Description: 15th-century mosque (1481) with unique zigzag minaret.

Name: Nyuserre_sun_temple
Description: 5th-dynasty sun temple (2420 BCE) at Abu Ghurab. Alabaster altar remains.

Name: Luxor_Museum
Description: Modern museum displaying Luxor Temple statues and New Kingdom artifacts.

Name: Aswan_Low_Dam
Description: 1902 British-built dam (1,900m long). Predecessor to High Dam.

Name: Pyramid_of_Senusret_I
Description: 12th-dynasty pyramid (1950 BCE) at Lisht. White limestone casing remnants.

Name: Tomb_of_Kheruef
Description: 18th-dynasty tomb (TT192) with festival scenes. Served Amenhotep III's steward.

Name: Sadat_museum
Description: Memorial museum for President Sadat. Displays personal items and assassination footage.

Name: Temple_of_Isis_in_Deir_el-Shelwit
Description: Roman-era Isis temple (1st century CE). Last pagan temple built in Egypt.

Name: Al-Aqmar_Mosque
Description: 12th-century Fatimid mosque (1125). First with decorated street facade.

Name: White_Monastery
Description: 4th-century Coptic monastery. Known for white limestone architecture.

Name: Antoniadis_Palace
Description: 19th-century palace with botanical gardens. European-style in Alexandria.

Name: Mosque_of_Qanibay_al-Rammah
Description: 15th-century Mamluk mosque (1503). Unique star-shaped minaret.

Name: Muhammad_Ali_Mosque
Description: 19th-century Ottoman mosque (1848). Alabaster courtyard and clock tower.

Name: Mosque_of_Sultan_al-Zahir_Baybars
